		{"id":"b99111b716ff81c9","type":"text","text":"# Allow Or Deny Selected Group\nLet's add group first\n\n```\n1. groupadd my_linux\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ Added a group having name my_linux\n\n2. cat /etc/group | grep my_linux\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ Seeing whether group is added or not\n\n3. useradd test_1; useradd test_2\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ Adding users for adding into groups\n\n4. id test_1\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ Will show all info about test_1 users like total groups and all\n\n5. echo \"redhat\" | passwd --stdin test_1\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ repeat same for user test_2\n\n--------------- Now you can add test_1 and test_2 directly on file /etc/group or can add using CLI command ----------------\n\n6. vim /etc/group\nğŸ‘‡ğŸ‘‡ see below\n\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250214213754.png]]\n\n```\n7. useradd -G my_linux aditya\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ creating and adding user aditya on group my_linux using CLI\n\n8. usermod -a -G my_linux vishal\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ Adding vishal in my_linux group\n```\n### Let's allow Groups to SSH\nWhen we allow users to SSH others users automatically deny for SSH\n\n```\n1. vim /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ So here we are going to allow users for SSH\n\n2. AllowGroups my_linux\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ This entry goes inside the sshd_config file it will allow group my_linux users only to ssh and deny every other groups users to ssh\nğŸ‘ˆğŸ‘ˆ see alongside\n\n3. systemctl restart sshd\nğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ It will restart the ssh service\n```","x":-320,"y":-285,"width":700,"height":1345,"color":"3"},
